51static void gldelf_iamcu_before_parse (void);
52static void gldelf_iamcu_after_parse (void);
53static void gldelf_iamcu_after_open (void);
54static void gldelf_iamcu_before_allocation (void);

57 (asection *, const char *, int);

59static void
60gldelf_iamcu_map_segments (bfd_boolean need_layout)
61{
62 int tries = 10;
63
64 do
65 {
66 lang_relax_sections (need_layout);
67 need_layout = FALSE;
68
69 if (link_info.output_bfd->xvec->flavour == bfd_target_elf_flavour
70 && !bfd_link_relocatable (&link_info))
71 {
72 bfd_size_type phdr_size;
73
74 phdr_size = elf_program_header_size (link_info.output_bfd);
75 /* If we don't have user supplied phdrs, throw away any
76 previous linker generated program headers. */
77 if (lang_phdr_list == NULL)
78 elf_seg_map (link_info.output_bfd) = NULL;
79 if (!_bfd_elf_map_sections_to_segments (link_info.output_bfd,
80 &link_info))
81 einfo (_("%F%P: map sections to segments failed: %E\n"));
82
83 if (phdr_size != elf_program_header_size (link_info.output_bfd))
84 {
85 if (tries > 6)
86 /* The first few times we allow any change to
87 phdr_size . */
88 need_layout = TRUE;
89 else if (phdr_size
90 < elf_program_header_size (link_info.output_bfd))
91 /* After that we only allow the size to grow. */
92 need_layout = TRUE;
93 else
94 elf_program_header_size (link_info.output_bfd) = phdr_size;
95 }
96 }
97 }
98 while (need_layout && --tries);
99
100 if (tries == 0)
101 einfo (_("%F%P: looping in map_segments"));
102}

104static void
105gldelf_iamcu_before_parse (void)
106{
107 ldfile_set_output_arch ("iamcu", bfd_arch_iamcu);
108 input_flags.dynamic = TRUE;
109 input_flags.add_DT_NEEDED_for_dynamic = TRUE;
110 config.has_shared = TRUE;
111 config.separate_code = FALSE;
112 link_info.call_nop_byte = 0x67;
113 link_info.check_relocs_after_open_input = TRUE;
114 link_info.relro = DEFAULT_LD_Z_RELRO;
115 link_info.separate_code = DEFAULT_LD_Z_SEPARATE_CODE;
116}

119static void
120gldelf_iamcu_after_parse (void)
121{
122 if (bfd_link_pie (&link_info))
123 link_info.flags_1 |= (bfd_vma) DF_1_PIE;
124
125 if (bfd_link_executable (&link_info)
126 && link_info.nointerp)
127 {
128 if (link_info.dynamic_undefined_weak > 0)
129 einfo (_("%P: warning: -z dynamic-undefined-weak ignored\n"));
130 link_info.dynamic_undefined_weak = 0;
131 }
132 after_parse_default ();
133}

135/* Handle the generation of DT_NEEDED tags. */
136
137static bfd_boolean
138gldelf_iamcu_load_symbols (lang_input_statement_type *entry)
139{
140 int link_class = 0;
141
142 /* Tell the ELF linker that we don't want the output file to have a
143 DT_NEEDED entry for this file, unless it is used to resolve
144 references in a regular object. */
145 if (entry->flags.add_DT_NEEDED_for_regular)
146 link_class = DYN_AS_NEEDED;
147
148 /* Tell the ELF linker that we don't want the output file to have a
149 DT_NEEDED entry for any dynamic library in DT_NEEDED tags from
150 this file at all. */
151 if (!entry->flags.add_DT_NEEDED_for_dynamic)
152 link_class |= DYN_NO_ADD_NEEDED;
153
154 if (entry->flags.just_syms
155 && (bfd_get_file_flags (entry->the_bfd) & DYNAMIC) != 0)
156 einfo (_("%F%P: %pB: --just-symbols may not be used on DSO\n"),
157 entry->the_bfd);
158
159 if (link_class == 0
160 || (bfd_get_file_flags (entry->the_bfd) & DYNAMIC) == 0)
161 return FALSE;
162
163 bfd_elf_set_dyn_lib_class (entry->the_bfd,
164 (enum dynamic_lib_link_class) link_class);
165
166 /* Continue on with normal load_symbols processing. */
167 return FALSE;
168}

170/* These variables are required to pass information back and forth
171 between after_open and check_needed and stat_needed and vercheck. */
172
173static struct bfd_link_needed_list *global_needed;
174static struct stat global_stat;
175static lang_input_statement_type *global_found;
176static struct bfd_link_needed_list *global_vercheck_needed;
177static bfd_boolean global_vercheck_failed;
178
179/* These variables are used to implement target options */
180
181static char *audit; /* colon (typically) separated list of libs */
182static char *depaudit; /* colon (typically) separated list of libs */
183
184/* Style of .note.gnu.build-id section. */
185static const char *emit_note_gnu_build_id;
186
187/* On Linux, it's possible to have different versions of the same
188 shared library linked against different versions of libc. The
189 dynamic linker somehow tags which libc version to use in
190 /etc/ld.so.cache, and, based on the libc that it sees in the
191 executable, chooses which version of the shared library to use.
192
193 We try to do a similar check here by checking whether this shared
194 library needs any other shared libraries which may conflict with
195 libraries we have already included in the link. If it does, we
196 skip it, and try to find another shared library farther on down the
197 link path.
198
199 This is called via lang_for_each_input_file.
200 GLOBAL_VERCHECK_NEEDED is the list of objects needed by the object
201 which we are checking. This sets GLOBAL_VERCHECK_FAILED if we find
202 a conflicting version. */
203
204static void
205gldelf_iamcu_vercheck (lang_input_statement_type *s)
206{
207 const char *soname;
208 struct bfd_link_needed_list *l;
209
210 if (global_vercheck_failed)
211 return;
212 if (s->the_bfd == NULL
213 || (bfd_get_file_flags (s->the_bfd) & DYNAMIC) == 0)
214 return;
215
216 soname = bfd_elf_get_dt_soname (s->the_bfd);
217 if (soname == NULL)
218 soname = lbasename (bfd_get_filename (s->the_bfd));
219
220 for (l = global_vercheck_needed; l != NULL; l = l->next)
221 {
222 const char *suffix;
223
224 if (filename_cmp (soname, l->name) == 0)
225 {
226 /* Probably can't happen, but it's an easy check. */
227 continue;
228 }
229
230 if (strchr (l->name, '/') != NULL)
231 continue;
232
233 suffix = strstr (l->name, ".so.");
234 if (suffix == NULL)
235 continue;
236
237 suffix += sizeof ".so." - 1;
238
239 if (filename_ncmp (soname, l->name, suffix - l->name) == 0)
240 {
241 /* Here we know that S is a dynamic object FOO.SO.VER1, and
242 the object we are considering needs a dynamic object
243 FOO.SO.VER2, and VER1 and VER2 are different. This
244 appears to be a version mismatch, so we tell the caller
245 to try a different version of this library. */
246 global_vercheck_failed = TRUE;
247 return;
248 }
249 }
250}

252
253/* See if an input file matches a DT_NEEDED entry by running stat on
254 the file. */
255
256static void
257gldelf_iamcu_stat_needed (lang_input_statement_type *s)
258{
259 struct stat st;
260 const char *suffix;
261 const char *soname;
262
263 if (global_found != NULL)
264 return;
265 if (s->the_bfd == NULL)
266 return;
267
268 /* If this input file was an as-needed entry, and wasn't found to be
269 needed at the stage it was linked, then don't say we have loaded it. */
270 if ((bfd_elf_get_dyn_lib_class (s->the_bfd) & DYN_AS_NEEDED) != 0)
271 return;
272
273 if (bfd_stat (s->the_bfd, &st) != 0)
274 {
275 einfo (_("%P: %pB: bfd_stat failed: %E\n"), s->the_bfd);
276 return;
277 }
278
279 /* Some operating systems, e.g. Windows, do not provide a meaningful
280 st_ino; they always set it to zero. (Windows does provide a
281 meaningful st_dev.) Do not indicate a duplicate library in that
282 case. While there is no guarantee that a system that provides
283 meaningful inode numbers will never set st_ino to zero, this is
284 merely an optimization, so we do not need to worry about false
285 negatives. */
286 if (st.st_dev == global_stat.st_dev
287 && st.st_ino == global_stat.st_ino
288 && st.st_ino != 0)
289 {
290 global_found = s;
291 return;
292 }
293
294 /* We issue a warning if it looks like we are including two
295 different versions of the same shared library. For example,
296 there may be a problem if -lc picks up libc.so.6 but some other
297 shared library has a DT_NEEDED entry of libc.so.5. This is a
298 heuristic test, and it will only work if the name looks like
299 NAME.so.VERSION. FIXME: Depending on file names is error-prone.
300 If we really want to issue warnings about mixing version numbers
301 of shared libraries, we need to find a better way. */
302
303 if (strchr (global_needed->name, '/') != NULL)
304 return;
305 suffix = strstr (global_needed->name, ".so.");
306 if (suffix == NULL)
307 return;
308 suffix += sizeof ".so." - 1;
309
310 soname = bfd_elf_get_dt_soname (s->the_bfd);
311 if (soname == NULL)
312 soname = lbasename (s->filename);
313
314 if (filename_ncmp (soname, global_needed->name, suffix - global_needed->name) == 0)
315 einfo (_("%P: warning: %s, needed by %pB, may conflict with %s\n"),
316 global_needed->name, global_needed->by, soname);
317}
318
319struct dt_needed
320{
321 bfd *by;
322 const char *name;
323};
324
325/* This function is called for each possible name for a dynamic object
326 named by a DT_NEEDED entry. The FORCE parameter indicates whether
327 to skip the check for a conflicting version. */
328
329static bfd_boolean
330gldelf_iamcu_try_needed (struct dt_needed *needed,
331 int force)
332{
333 bfd *abfd;
334 const char *name = needed->name;
335 const char *soname;
336 int link_class;
337
338 abfd = bfd_openr (name, bfd_get_target (link_info.output_bfd));
339 if (abfd == NULL)
340 {
341 if (verbose)
342 info_msg (_("attempt to open %s failed\n"), name);
343 return FALSE;
344 }
345
346 /* Linker needs to decompress sections. */
347 abfd->flags |= BFD_DECOMPRESS;
348
349 if (! bfd_check_format (abfd, bfd_object))
350 {
351 bfd_close (abfd);
352 return FALSE;
353 }
354 if ((bfd_get_file_flags (abfd) & DYNAMIC) == 0)
355 {
356 bfd_close (abfd);
357 return FALSE;
358 }
359
360 /* For DT_NEEDED, they have to match. */
361 if (abfd->xvec != link_info.output_bfd->xvec)
362 {
363 bfd_close (abfd);
364 return FALSE;
365 }
366
367 /* Check whether this object would include any conflicting library
368 versions. If FORCE is set, then we skip this check; we use this
369 the second time around, if we couldn't find any compatible
370 instance of the shared library. */
371
372 if (! force)
373 {
374 struct bfd_link_needed_list *needs;
375
376 if (! bfd_elf_get_bfd_needed_list (abfd, &needs))
377 einfo (_("%F%P: %pB: bfd_elf_get_bfd_needed_list failed: %E\n"), abfd);
378
379 if (needs != NULL)
380 {
381 global_vercheck_needed = needs;
382 global_vercheck_failed = FALSE;
383 lang_for_each_input_file (gldelf_iamcu_vercheck);
384 if (global_vercheck_failed)
385 {
386 bfd_close (abfd);
387 /* Return FALSE to force the caller to move on to try
388 another file on the search path. */
389 return FALSE;
390 }
391
392 /* But wait! It gets much worse. On Linux, if a shared
393 library does not use libc at all, we are supposed to skip
394 it the first time around in case we encounter a shared
395 library later on with the same name which does use the
396 version of libc that we want. This is much too horrible
397 to use on any system other than Linux. */
398
399 }
400 }
401
402 /* We've found a dynamic object matching the DT_NEEDED entry. */
403
404 /* We have already checked that there is no other input file of the
405 same name. We must now check again that we are not including the
406 same file twice. We need to do this because on many systems
407 libc.so is a symlink to, e.g., libc.so.1. The SONAME entry will
408 reference libc.so.1. If we have already included libc.so, we
409 don't want to include libc.so.1 if they are the same file, and we
410 can only check that using stat. */
411
412 if (bfd_stat (abfd, &global_stat) != 0)
413 einfo (_("%F%P: %pB: bfd_stat failed: %E\n"), abfd);
414
415 /* First strip off everything before the last '/'. */
416 soname = lbasename (abfd->filename);
417
418 if (verbose)
419 info_msg (_("found %s at %s\n"), soname, name);
420
421 global_found = NULL;
422 lang_for_each_input_file (gldelf_iamcu_stat_needed);
423 if (global_found != NULL)
424 {
425 /* Return TRUE to indicate that we found the file, even though
426 we aren't going to do anything with it. */
427 return TRUE;
428 }
429
430 /* Specify the soname to use. */
431 bfd_elf_set_dt_needed_name (abfd, soname);
432
433 /* Tell the ELF linker that we don't want the output file to have a
434 DT_NEEDED entry for this file, unless it is used to resolve
435 references in a regular object. */
436 link_class = DYN_DT_NEEDED;
437
438 /* Tell the ELF linker that we don't want the output file to have a
439 DT_NEEDED entry for this file at all if the entry is from a file
440 with DYN_NO_ADD_NEEDED. */
441 if (needed->by != NULL
442 && (bfd_elf_get_dyn_lib_class (needed->by) & DYN_NO_ADD_NEEDED) != 0)
443 link_class |= DYN_NO_NEEDED | DYN_NO_ADD_NEEDED;
444
445 bfd_elf_set_dyn_lib_class (abfd, (enum dynamic_lib_link_class) link_class);
446
447 /* Add this file into the symbol table. */
448 if (! bfd_link_add_symbols (abfd, &link_info))
449 einfo (_("%F%P: %pB: error adding symbols: %E\n"), abfd);
450
451 return TRUE;
452}
453
454/* Search for a needed file in a path. */
455
456static bfd_boolean
457gldelf_iamcu_search_needed (const char *path,
458 struct dt_needed *n, int force, int prepend_sysroot)
459{
460 const char *s;
461 const char *name = n->name;
462 size_t len;
463 struct dt_needed needed;
464
465 if (name[0] == '/') {
466 if (prepend_sysroot && ld_sysroot) {
467 bfd_boolean rv;
468 needed.by = n->by;
469 char *filename= concat(ld_sysroot, n->name, (const char *)NULL);
470 needed.name = filename;
471 rv = gldelf_iamcu_try_needed (&needed, force);
472 free(filename);
473 return rv;
474 }
475 return gldelf_iamcu_try_needed (n, force);
476 }
477
478 if (path == NULL || *path == '\0')
479 return FALSE;
480
481 needed.by = n->by;
482 needed.name = n->name;
483
484 len = strlen (name);
485 while (1)
486 {
487 unsigned offset = 0;
488 char * var;
489 char *filename, *sset;
490
491 s = strchr (path, config.rpath_separator);
492 if (s == NULL)
493 s = path + strlen (path);
494
495#if HAVE_DOS_BASED_FILE_SYSTEM
496 /* Assume a match on the second char is part of drive specifier. */
497 else if (config.rpath_separator == ':'
498 && s == path + 1
499 && ISALPHA (*path))
500 {
501 s = strchr (s + 1, config.rpath_separator);
502 if (s == NULL)
503 s = path + strlen (path);
504 }
505#endif
506 filename = (char *) xmalloc (s - path + len + 2);
507 if (s == path)
508 sset = filename;
509 else
510 {
511 memcpy (filename, path, s - path);
512 filename[s - path] = '/';
513 sset = filename + (s - path) + 1;
514 }
515 strcpy (sset, name);
516
517 if (prepend_sysroot && filename[0] == '=')
518 abort();
519 if (filename[0] == '/' && prepend_sysroot && ld_sysroot) {
520 char *filename2 = concat(ld_sysroot, filename, (const char *)NULL);
521 free(filename);
522 filename = filename2;
523 }
524 /* PR 20535: Support the same pseudo-environment variables that
525 are supported by ld.so. Namely, , and .
526 Since there can be more than one occurrence of these tokens in
527 the path we loop until no more are found. Since we might not
528 be able to substitute some of the tokens we maintain an offset
529 into the filename for where we should begin our scan. */
530 while ((var = strchr (filename + offset, '$')) != NULL)
531 {
532 /* The ld.so manual page does not say, but I am going to assume that
533 these tokens are terminated by a directory separator character
534 (/) or the end of the string. There is also an implication that
535 should only be used at the start of a path, but that is
536 not enforced here.
537
538 The ld.so manual page also states that it allows ,
539 and , so these are supported as well.
540
541 FIXME: The code could be a lot cleverer about allocating space
542 for the processed string. */
543 char * end = strchr (var, '/');
544 char * replacement = NULL;
545 char * v = var + 1;
546 char * freeme = NULL;
547 unsigned flen = strlen (filename);
548
549 if (end != NULL)
550 /* Temporarily terminate the filename at the end of the token. */
551 * end = 0;
552
553 if (*v == '{')
554 ++ v;
555 switch (*v++)
556 {
557 case 'O':
558 if (strcmp (v, "RIGIN") == 0 || strcmp (v, "RIGIN}") == 0)
559 {
560 /* ORIGIN - replace with the full path to the directory
561 containing the program or shared object. */
562 if (needed.by == NULL)
563 {
564 if (link_info.output_bfd == NULL)
565 {
566 break;
567 }
568 else
569 replacement = bfd_get_filename (link_info.output_bfd);
570 }
571 else
572 replacement = bfd_get_filename (needed.by);
573
574 if (replacement)
575 {
576 char * slash;
577
578 if (replacement[0] == '/')
579 freeme = xstrdup (replacement);
580 else
581 {
582 char * current_dir = getpwd ();
583
584 freeme = xmalloc (strlen (replacement) + strlen (current_dir) + 2);
585 sprintf (freeme, "%s/%s", current_dir, replacement);
586 }
587
588 replacement = freeme;
589 if ((slash = strrchr (replacement, '/')) != NULL)
590 * slash = 0;
591 }
592 }
593 break;
594
595 case 'L':
596 if (strcmp (v, "IB") == 0 || strcmp (v, "IB}") == 0)
597 {
598 /* LIB - replace with "lib" in 32-bit environments
599 and "lib64" in 64-bit environments. */
600
601 /* Note - we could replace this switch statement by
602 conditional fragments of shell script, but that is messy.
603 Any compiler worth its salt is going to optimize away
604 all but one of these case statements anyway. */
605 switch (32)
606 {
607 case 32: replacement = "lib"; break;
608 case 64: replacement = "lib64"; break;
609 default:
610 /* 32 is not 32 or 64 ... */
611 abort ();
612 }
613 }
614 break;
615
616 case 'P':
617 /* Supporting in a cross-hosted environment is not
618 possible. Supporting it in a native environment involves
619 loading the <sys/auxv.h> header file which loads the
620 system <elf.h> header file, which conflicts with the
621 "include/elf/mips.h" header file. */
622 /* Fall through. */
623 default:
624 break;
625 }
626
627 if (replacement)
628 {
629 char * filename2 = xmalloc (flen + strlen (replacement));
630
631 if (end)
632 {
633 sprintf (filename2, "%.*s%s/%s",
634 (int)(var - filename), filename,
635 replacement, end + 1);
636 offset = (var - filename) + 1 + strlen (replacement);
637 }
638 else
639 {
640 sprintf (filename2, "%.*s%s",
641 (int)(var - filename), filename,
642 replacement);
643 offset = var - filename + strlen (replacement);
644 }
645
646 free (filename);
647 filename = filename2;
648 /* There is no need to restore the path separator (when
649 end != NULL) as we have replaced the entire string. */
650 }
651 else
652 {
653 if (verbose)
654 /* We only issue an "unrecognised" message in verbose mode
655 as the $<foo> token might be a legitimate component of
656 a path name in the target's file system. */
657 info_msg (_("unrecognised or unsupported token '%s' in search path\n"), var);
658
659 if (end)
660 /* Restore the path separator. */
661 * end = '/';
662
663 /* PR 20784: Make sure that we resume the scan *after*
664 the token that we could not replace. */
665 offset = (var + 1) - filename;
666 }
667
668 free (freeme);
669 }
670
671 needed.name = filename;
672
673 if (gldelf_iamcu_try_needed (&needed, force))
674 return TRUE;
675
676 free (filename);
677
678 if (*s == '\0')
679 break;
680 path = s + 1;
681 }
682
683 return FALSE;
684}
685
686
687/* Prefix the sysroot to absolute paths in PATH, a string containing
688 paths separated by config.rpath_separator. If running on a DOS
689 file system, paths containing a drive spec won't have the sysroot
690 prefix added, unless the sysroot also specifies the same drive. */
691
692static const char *
693gldelf_iamcu_add_sysroot (const char *path)
694{
695 size_t len, extra;
696 const char *p;
697 char *ret, *q;
698 int dos_drive_sysroot = HAS_DRIVE_SPEC (ld_sysroot);
699
700 len = strlen (ld_sysroot);
701 for (extra = 0, p = path; ; )
702 {
703 int dos_drive = HAS_DRIVE_SPEC (p);
704
705 if (dos_drive)
706 p += 2;
707 if (IS_DIR_SEPARATOR (*p)
708 && (!dos_drive
709 || (dos_drive_sysroot
710 && ld_sysroot[0] == p[-2])))
711 {
712 if (dos_drive && dos_drive_sysroot)
713 extra += len - 2;
714 else
715 extra += len;
716 }
717 p = strchr (p, config.rpath_separator);
718 if (!p)
719 break;
720 ++p;
721 }
722
723 ret = xmalloc (strlen (path) + extra + 1);
724
725 for (q = ret, p = path; ; )
726 {
727 const char *end;
728 int dos_drive = HAS_DRIVE_SPEC (p);
729
730 if (dos_drive)
731 {
732 *q++ = *p++;
733 *q++ = *p++;
734 }
735 if (IS_DIR_SEPARATOR (*p)
736 && (!dos_drive
737 || (dos_drive_sysroot
738 && ld_sysroot[0] == p[-2])))
739 {
740 if (dos_drive && dos_drive_sysroot)
741 {
742 strcpy (q, ld_sysroot + 2);
743 q += len - 2;
744 }
745 else
746 {
747 strcpy (q, ld_sysroot);
748 q += len;
749 }
750 }
751 end = strchr (p, config.rpath_separator);
752 if (end)
753 {
754 size_t n = end - p + 1;
755 strncpy (q, p, n);
756 q += n;
757 p += n;
758 }
759 else
760 {
761 strcpy (q, p);
762 break;
763 }
764 }
765
766 return ret;
767}
768
769
770/* See if an input file matches a DT_NEEDED entry by name. */
771
772static void
773gldelf_iamcu_check_needed (lang_input_statement_type *s)
774{
775 const char *soname;
776
777 /* Stop looking if we've found a loaded lib. */
778 if (global_found != NULL
779 && (bfd_elf_get_dyn_lib_class (global_found->the_bfd)
780 & DYN_AS_NEEDED) == 0)
781 return;
782
783 if (s->filename == NULL || s->the_bfd == NULL)
784 return;
785
786 /* Don't look for a second non-loaded as-needed lib. */
787 if (global_found != NULL
788 && (bfd_elf_get_dyn_lib_class (s->the_bfd) & DYN_AS_NEEDED) != 0)
789 return;
790
791 if (filename_cmp (s->filename, global_needed->name) == 0)
792 {
793 global_found = s;
794 return;
795 }
796
797 if (s->flags.search_dirs)
798 {
799 const char *f = strrchr (s->filename, '/');
800 if (f != NULL
801 && filename_cmp (f + 1, global_needed->name) == 0)
802 {
803 global_found = s;
804 return;
805 }
806 }
807
808 soname = bfd_elf_get_dt_soname (s->the_bfd);
809 if (soname != NULL
810 && filename_cmp (soname, global_needed->name) == 0)
811 {
812 global_found = s;
813 return;
814 }
815}
816
817
818static bfd_size_type
819id_note_section_size (bfd *abfd ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED)
820{
821 const char *style = emit_note_gnu_build_id;
822 bfd_size_type size;
823 bfd_size_type build_id_size;
824
825 size = offsetof (Elf_External_Note, name[sizeof "GNU"]);
826 size = (size + 3) & -(bfd_size_type) 4;
827
828 build_id_size = compute_build_id_size (style);
829 if (build_id_size)
830 size += build_id_size;
831 else
832 size = 0;
833
834 return size;
835}
836
837static bfd_boolean
838write_build_id (bfd *abfd)
839{
840 const struct elf_backend_data *bed = get_elf_backend_data (abfd);
841 struct elf_obj_tdata *t = elf_tdata (abfd);
842 const char *style;
843 asection *asec;
844 Elf_Internal_Shdr *i_shdr;
845 unsigned char *contents, *id_bits;
846 bfd_size_type size;
847 file_ptr position;
848 Elf_External_Note *e_note;
849
850 style = t->o->build_id.style;
851 asec = t->o->build_id.sec;
852 if (bfd_is_abs_section (asec->output_section))
853 {
854 einfo (_("%P: warning: .note.gnu.build-id section discarded,"
855 " --build-id ignored\n"));
856 return TRUE;
857 }
858 i_shdr = &elf_section_data (asec->output_section)->this_hdr;
859
860 if (i_shdr->contents == NULL)
861 {
862 if (asec->contents == NULL)
863 asec->contents = (unsigned char *) xmalloc (asec->size);
864 contents = asec->contents;
865 }
866 else
867 contents = i_shdr->contents + asec->output_offset;
868
869 e_note = (Elf_External_Note *) contents;
870 size = offsetof (Elf_External_Note, name[sizeof "GNU"]);
871 size = (size + 3) & -(bfd_size_type) 4;
872 id_bits = contents + size;
873 size = asec->size - size;
874
875 bfd_h_put_32 (abfd, sizeof "GNU", &e_note->namesz);
876 bfd_h_put_32 (abfd, size, &e_note->descsz);
877 bfd_h_put_32 (abfd, NT_GNU_BUILD_ID, &e_note->type);
878 memcpy (e_note->name, "GNU", sizeof "GNU");
879
880 generate_build_id (abfd, style, bed->s->checksum_contents, id_bits, size);
881
882 position = i_shdr->sh_offset + asec->output_offset;
883 size = asec->size;
884 return (bfd_seek (abfd, position, SEEK_SET) == 0
885 && bfd_bwrite (contents, size, abfd) == size);
886}
887
888/* Make .note.gnu.build-id section, and set up elf_tdata->build_id. */
889
890static bfd_boolean
891setup_build_id (bfd *ibfd)
892{
893 asection *s;
894 bfd_size_type size;
895 flagword flags;
896
897 size = id_note_section_size (ibfd);
898 if (size == 0)
899 {
900 einfo (_("%P: warning: unrecognized --build-id style ignored\n"));
901 return FALSE;
902 }
903
904 flags = (SEC_ALLOC | SEC_LOAD | SEC_IN_MEMORY
905 | SEC_LINKER_CREATED | SEC_READONLY | SEC_DATA);
906 s = bfd_make_section_with_flags (ibfd, ".note.gnu.build-id", flags);
907 if (s != NULL && bfd_set_section_alignment (ibfd, s, 2))
908 {
909 struct elf_obj_tdata *t = elf_tdata (link_info.output_bfd);
910 t->o->build_id.after_write_object_contents = &write_build_id;
911 t->o->build_id.style = emit_note_gnu_build_id;
912 t->o->build_id.sec = s;
913 elf_section_type (s) = SHT_NOTE;
914 s->size = size;
915 return TRUE;
916 }
917
918 einfo (_("%P: warning: cannot create .note.gnu.build-id section,"
919 " --build-id ignored\n"));
920 return FALSE;
921}
922
923/* This is called after all the input files have been opened. */
924
925static void
926gldelf_iamcu_after_open (void)
927{
928 struct bfd_link_needed_list *needed, *l;
929 struct elf_link_hash_table *htab;
930 asection *s;
931 bfd *abfd;
932
933 after_open_default ();
934
935 htab = elf_hash_table (&link_info);
936 if (!is_elf_hash_table (htab))
937 return;
938
939 if (command_line.out_implib_filename)
940 {
941 unlink_if_ordinary (command_line.out_implib_filename);
942 link_info.out_implib_bfd
943 = bfd_openw (command_line.out_implib_filename,
944 bfd_get_target (link_info.output_bfd));
945
946 if (link_info.out_implib_bfd == NULL)
947 {
948 einfo (_("%F%P: %s: can't open for writing: %E\n"),
949 command_line.out_implib_filename);
950 }
951 }
952
953 if (emit_note_gnu_build_id != NULL)
954 {
955 /* Find an ELF input. */
956 for (abfd = link_info.input_bfds;
957 abfd != (bfd *) NULL; abfd = abfd->link.next)
958 if (bfd_get_flavour (abfd) == bfd_target_elf_flavour
959 && bfd_count_sections (abfd) != 0
960 && !((lang_input_statement_type *) abfd->usrdata)->flags.just_syms)
961 break;
962
963 /* PR 10555: If there are no ELF input files do not try to
964 create a .note.gnu-build-id section. */
965 if (abfd == NULL
966 || !setup_build_id (abfd))
967 {
968 free ((char *) emit_note_gnu_build_id);
969 emit_note_gnu_build_id = NULL;
970 }
971 }
972
973 get_elf_backend_data (link_info.output_bfd)->setup_gnu_properties (&link_info);
974
975 if (bfd_link_relocatable (&link_info))
976 {
977 if (link_info.execstack == ! link_info.noexecstack)
978 /* PR ld/16744: If "-z [no]execstack" has been specified on the
979 command line and we are perfoming a relocatable link then no
980 PT_GNU_STACK segment will be created and so the
981 linkinfo.[no]execstack values set in _handle_option() will have no
982 effect. Instead we create a .note.GNU-stack section in much the
983 same way as the assembler does with its --[no]execstack option. */
984 (void) bfd_make_section_with_flags (link_info.input_bfds,
985 ".note.GNU-stack",
986 SEC_READONLY | (link_info.execstack ? SEC_CODE : 0));
987
988 return;
989 }
990
991 if (!link_info.traditional_format)
992 {
993 bfd *elfbfd = NULL;
994 bfd_boolean warn_eh_frame = FALSE;
995 int seen_type = 0;
996
997 for (abfd = link_info.input_bfds; abfd; abfd = abfd->link.next)
998 {
999 int type = 0;
1000
1001 if (((lang_input_statement_type *) abfd->usrdata)->flags.just_syms)
1002 continue;
1003
1004 for (s = abfd->sections; s && type < COMPACT_EH_HDR; s = s->next)
1005 {
1006 const char *name = bfd_get_section_name (abfd, s);
1007
1008 if (bfd_is_abs_section (s->output_section))
1009 continue;
1010 if (CONST_STRNEQ (name, ".eh_frame_entry"))
1011 type = COMPACT_EH_HDR;
1012 else if (strcmp (name, ".eh_frame") == 0 && s->size > 8)
1013 type = DWARF2_EH_HDR;
1014 }
1015
1016 if (type != 0)
1017 {
1018 if (seen_type == 0)
1019 {
1020 seen_type = type;
1021 }
1022 else if (seen_type != type)
1023 {
1024 einfo (_("%F%P: compact frame descriptions incompatible with"
1025 " DWARF2 .eh_frame from %pB\n"),
1026 type == DWARF2_EH_HDR ? abfd : elfbfd);
1027 break;
1028 }
1029
1030 if (!elfbfd
1031 && (type == COMPACT_EH_HDR || link_info.eh_frame_hdr_type != 0))
1032 {
1033 if (bfd_get_flavour (abfd) == bfd_target_elf_flavour)
1034 elfbfd = abfd;
1035
1036 warn_eh_frame = TRUE;
1037 }
1038 }
1039
1040 if (seen_type == COMPACT_EH_HDR)
1041 link_info.eh_frame_hdr_type = COMPACT_EH_HDR;
1042 }
1043 if (elfbfd)
1044 {
1045 const struct elf_backend_data *bed;
1046
1047 bed = get_elf_backend_data (elfbfd);
1048 s = bfd_make_section_with_flags (elfbfd, ".eh_frame_hdr",
1049 bed->dynamic_sec_flags
1050 | SEC_READONLY);
1051 if (s != NULL
1052 && bfd_set_section_alignment (elfbfd, s, 2))
1053 {
1054 htab->eh_info.hdr_sec = s;
1055 warn_eh_frame = FALSE;
1056 }
1057 }
1058 if (warn_eh_frame)
1059 einfo (_("%P: warning: cannot create .eh_frame_hdr section,"
1060 " --eh-frame-hdr ignored\n"));
1061 }
1062
1063 /* Get the list of files which appear in DT_NEEDED entries in
1064 dynamic objects included in the link (often there will be none).
1065 For each such file, we want to track down the corresponding
1066 library, and include the symbol table in the link. This is what
1067 the runtime dynamic linker will do. Tracking the files down here
1068 permits one dynamic object to include another without requiring
1069 special action by the person doing the link. Note that the
1070 needed list can actually grow while we are stepping through this
1071 loop. */
1072 needed = bfd_elf_get_needed_list (link_info.output_bfd, &link_info);
1073 for (l = needed; l != NULL; l = l->next)
1074 {
1075 struct bfd_link_needed_list *ll;
1076 struct dt_needed n, nn;
1077 int force;
1078
1079 /* If the lib that needs this one was --as-needed and wasn't
1080 found to be needed, then this lib isn't needed either. */
1081 if (l->by != NULL
1082 && (bfd_elf_get_dyn_lib_class (l->by) & DYN_AS_NEEDED) != 0)
1083 continue;
1084
1085 /* Skip the lib if --no-copy-dt-needed-entries and
1086 --allow-shlib-undefined is in effect. */
1087 if (l->by != NULL
1088 && link_info.unresolved_syms_in_shared_libs == RM_IGNORE
1089 && (bfd_elf_get_dyn_lib_class (l->by) & DYN_NO_ADD_NEEDED) != 0)
1090 continue;
1091
1092 /* If we've already seen this file, skip it. */
1093 for (ll = needed; ll != l; ll = ll->next)
1094 if ((ll->by == NULL
1095 || (bfd_elf_get_dyn_lib_class (ll->by) & DYN_AS_NEEDED) == 0)
1096 && strcmp (ll->name, l->name) == 0)
1097 break;
1098 if (ll != l)
1099 continue;
1100
1101 /* See if this file was included in the link explicitly. */
1102 global_needed = l;
1103 global_found = NULL;
1104 lang_for_each_input_file (gldelf_iamcu_check_needed);
1105 if (global_found != NULL
1106 && (bfd_elf_get_dyn_lib_class (global_found->the_bfd)
1107 & DYN_AS_NEEDED) == 0)
1108 continue;
1109
1110 n.by = l->by;
1111 n.name = l->name;
1112 nn.by = l->by;
1113 if (verbose)
1114 info_msg (_("%s needed by %pB\n"), l->name, l->by);
1115
1116 /* As-needed libs specified on the command line (or linker script)
1117 take priority over libs found in search dirs. */
1118 if (global_found != NULL)
1119 {
1120 nn.name = global_found->filename;
1121 if (gldelf_iamcu_try_needed (&nn, TRUE))
1122 continue;
1123 }
1124
1125 /* We need to find this file and include the symbol table. We
1126 want to search for the file in the same way that the dynamic
1127 linker will search. That means that we want to use
1128 rpath_link, rpath, then the environment variable
1129 LD_LIBRARY_PATH (native only), then the DT_RPATH/DT_RUNPATH
1130 entries (native only), then the linker script LIB_SEARCH_DIRS.
1131 We do not search using the -L arguments.
1132
1133 We search twice. The first time, we skip objects which may
1134 introduce version mismatches. The second time, we force
1135 their use. See gldelf_iamcu_vercheck comment. */
1136 for (force = 0; force < 2; force++)
1137 {
1138 size_t len;
1139 search_dirs_type *search;
1140 const char *path;
1141 struct bfd_link_needed_list *rp;
1142 int found;
1143
1144 if (gldelf_iamcu_search_needed (command_line.rpath_link,
1145 &n, force, 0))
1146 break;
1147 path = command_line.rpath;
1148 if (path)
1149 {
1150 path = gldelf_iamcu_add_sysroot (path);
1151 found = gldelf_iamcu_search_needed (path, &n, force, 0);
1152 free ((char *) path);
1153 if (found)
1154 break;
1155 }
1156 if (command_line.rpath_link == NULL
1157 && command_line.rpath == NULL)
1158 {
1159 path = (const char *) getenv ("LD_RUN_PATH");
1160 if (path
1161 && gldelf_iamcu_search_needed (path, &n, force, 0))
1162 break;
1163 }
1164 path = (const char *) getenv ("LD_LIBRARY_PATH");
1165 if (path
1166 && gldelf_iamcu_search_needed (path, &n, force, 0))
1167 break;
1168 found = 0;
1169 rp = bfd_elf_get_runpath_list (link_info.output_bfd, &link_info);
1170 for (; !found && rp != NULL; rp = rp->next)
1171 {
1172 path = gldelf_iamcu_add_sysroot (rp->name);
1173 found = (rp->by == l->by
1174 && gldelf_iamcu_search_needed (path, &n,
1175 force, 1));
1176 free ((char *) path);
1177 }
1178 if (found)
1179 break;
1180
1181 len = strlen (l->name);
1182 for (search = search_head; search != NULL; search = search->next)
1183 {
1184 char *filename;
1185
1186 if (search->cmdline)
1187 continue;
1188 filename = (char *) xmalloc (strlen (search->name) + len + 2);
1189 sprintf (filename, "%s/%s", search->name, l->name);
1190 nn.name = filename;
1191 if (gldelf_iamcu_try_needed (&nn, force))
1192 break;
1193 free (filename);
1194 }
1195 if (search != NULL)
1196 break;
1197 }
1198
1199 if (force < 2)
1200 continue;
1201
1202 einfo (_("%P: warning: %s, needed by %pB, not found "
1203 "(try using -rpath or -rpath-link)\n"),
1204 l->name, l->by);
1205 }
1206
1207 if (link_info.eh_frame_hdr_type == COMPACT_EH_HDR)
1208 if (!bfd_elf_parse_eh_frame_entries (NULL, &link_info))
1209 einfo (_("%F%P: failed to parse EH frame entries\n"));
1210}
1211
1212
1213/* Look through an expression for an assignment statement. */
1214
1215static void
1216gldelf_iamcu_find_exp_assignment (etree_type *exp)
1217{
1218 bfd_boolean provide = FALSE;
1219
1220 switch (exp->type.node_class)
1221 {
1222 case etree_provide:
1223 case etree_provided:
1224 provide = TRUE;
1225 /* Fallthru */
1226 case etree_assign:
1227 /* We call record_link_assignment even if the symbol is defined.
1228 This is because if it is defined by a dynamic object, we
1229 actually want to use the value defined by the linker script,
1230 not the value from the dynamic object (because we are setting
1231 symbols like etext). If the symbol is defined by a regular
1232 object, then, as it happens, calling record_link_assignment
1233 will do no harm. */
1234 if (strcmp (exp->assign.dst, ".") != 0)
1235 {
1236 if (!bfd_elf_record_link_assignment (link_info.output_bfd,
1237 &link_info,
1238 exp->assign.dst, provide,
1239 exp->assign.hidden))
1240 einfo (_("%F%P: failed to record assignment to %s: %E\n"),
1241 exp->assign.dst);
1242 }
1243 gldelf_iamcu_find_exp_assignment (exp->assign.src);
1244 break;
1245
1246 case etree_binary:
1247 gldelf_iamcu_find_exp_assignment (exp->binary.lhs);
1248 gldelf_iamcu_find_exp_assignment (exp->binary.rhs);
1249 break;
1250
1251 case etree_trinary:
1252 gldelf_iamcu_find_exp_assignment (exp->trinary.cond);
1253 gldelf_iamcu_find_exp_assignment (exp->trinary.lhs);
1254 gldelf_iamcu_find_exp_assignment (exp->trinary.rhs);
1255 break;
1256
1257 case etree_unary:
1258 gldelf_iamcu_find_exp_assignment (exp->unary.child);
1259 break;
1260
1261 default:
1262 break;
1263 }
1264}
1265
1266
1267/* This is called by the before_allocation routine via
1268 lang_for_each_statement. It locates any assignment statements, and
1269 tells the ELF backend about them, in case they are assignments to
1270 symbols which are referred to by dynamic objects. */
1271
1272static void
1273gldelf_iamcu_find_statement_assignment (lang_statement_union_type *s)
1274{
1275 if (s->header.type == lang_assignment_statement_enum)
1276 gldelf_iamcu_find_exp_assignment (s->assignment_statement.exp);
1277}
1278
1279
1280/* used by before_allocation and handle_option. */
1281static void
1282gldelf_iamcu_append_to_separated_string (char **to, char *op_arg)
1283{
1284 if (*to == NULL)
1285 *to = xstrdup (op_arg);
1286 else
1287 {
1288 size_t to_len = strlen (*to);
1289 size_t op_arg_len = strlen (op_arg);
1290 char *buf;
1291 char *cp = *to;
1292
1293 /* First see whether OPTARG is already in the path. */
1294 do
1295 {
1296 if (strncmp (op_arg, cp, op_arg_len) == 0
1297 && (cp[op_arg_len] == 0
1298 || cp[op_arg_len] == config.rpath_separator))
1299 /* We found it. */
1300 break;
1301
1302 /* Not yet found. */
1303 cp = strchr (cp, config.rpath_separator);
1304 if (cp != NULL)
1305 ++cp;
1306 }
1307 while (cp != NULL);
1308
1309 if (cp == NULL)
1310 {
1311 buf = xmalloc (to_len + op_arg_len + 2);
1312 sprintf (buf, "%s%c%s", *to,
1313 config.rpath_separator, op_arg);
1314 free (*to);
1315 *to = buf;
1316 }
1317 }
1318}
1319
1320#if defined(__GNUC__) && GCC_VERSION < 4006
1321 /* Work around a GCC uninitialized warning bug fixed in GCC 4.6. */
1322static struct bfd_link_hash_entry ehdr_start_empty;
1323#endif
1324
1325/* This is called after the sections have been attached to output
1326 sections, but before any sizes or addresses have been set. */
1327
1328static void
1329gldelf_iamcu_before_allocation (void)
1330{
1331 const char *rpath;
1332 asection *sinterp;
1333 bfd *abfd;
1334 struct elf_link_hash_entry *ehdr_start = NULL;
1335#if defined(__GNUC__) && GCC_VERSION < 4006
1336 /* Work around a GCC uninitialized warning bug fixed in GCC 4.6. */
1337 struct bfd_link_hash_entry ehdr_start_save = ehdr_start_empty;
1338#else
1339 struct bfd_link_hash_entry ehdr_start_save;
1340#endif
1341
1342 if (is_elf_hash_table (link_info.hash))
1343 {
1344 _bfd_elf_tls_setup (link_info.output_bfd, &link_info);
1345
1346 /* Make __ehdr_start hidden if it has been referenced, to
1347 prevent the symbol from being dynamic. */
1348 if (!bfd_link_relocatable (&link_info))
1349 {
1350 struct elf_link_hash_table *htab = elf_hash_table (&link_info);
1351 struct elf_link_hash_entry *h
1352 = elf_link_hash_lookup (htab, "__ehdr_start", FALSE, FALSE, TRUE);
1353
1354 /* Only adjust the export class if the symbol was referenced
1355 and not defined, otherwise leave it alone. */
1356 if (h != NULL
1357 && (h->root.type == bfd_link_hash_new
1358 || h->root.type == bfd_link_hash_undefined
1359 || h->root.type == bfd_link_hash_undefweak
1360 || h->root.type == bfd_link_hash_common))
1361 {
1362 const struct elf_backend_data *bed;
1363 bed = get_elf_backend_data (link_info.output_bfd);
1364 (*bed->elf_backend_hide_symbol) (&link_info, h, TRUE);
1365 if (ELF_ST_VISIBILITY (h->other) != STV_INTERNAL)
1366 h->other = (h->other & ~ELF_ST_VISIBILITY (-1)) | STV_HIDDEN;
1367 /* Don't leave the symbol undefined. Undefined hidden
1368 symbols typically won't have dynamic relocations, but
1369 we most likely will need dynamic relocations for
1370 __ehdr_start if we are building a PIE or shared
1371 library. */
1372 ehdr_start = h;
1373 ehdr_start_save = h->root;
1374 h->root.type = bfd_link_hash_defined;
1375 h->root.u.def.section = bfd_abs_section_ptr;
1376 h->root.u.def.value = 0;
1377 }
1378 }
1379
1380 /* If we are going to make any variable assignments, we need to
1381 let the ELF backend know about them in case the variables are
1382 referred to by dynamic objects. */
1383 lang_for_each_statement (gldelf_iamcu_find_statement_assignment);
1384 }
1385
1386 /* Let the ELF backend work out the sizes of any sections required
1387 by dynamic linking. */
1388 rpath = command_line.rpath;
1389 if (rpath == NULL)
1390 rpath = (const char *) getenv ("LD_RUN_PATH");
1391
1392 for (abfd = link_info.input_bfds; abfd; abfd = abfd->link.next)
1393 if (bfd_get_flavour (abfd) == bfd_target_elf_flavour)
1394 {
1395 const char *audit_libs = elf_dt_audit (abfd);
1396
1397 /* If the input bfd contains an audit entry, we need to add it as
1398 a dep audit entry. */
1399 if (audit_libs && *audit_libs != '\0')
1400 {
1401 char *cp, *fcp;
1402 fcp = cp = xstrdup (audit_libs);
1403 do
1404 {
1405 int more = 0;
1406 char *cp2 = strchr (cp, config.rpath_separator);
1407
1408 if (cp2)
1409 {
1410 *cp2 = '\0';
1411 more = 1;
1412 }
1413
1414 if (cp != NULL && *cp != '\0')
1415 gldelf_iamcu_append_to_separated_string (&depaudit, cp);
1416
1417 cp = more ? ++cp2 : NULL;
1418 }
1419 while (cp != NULL);
1420 free (fcp);
1421 }
1422 }
1423
1424 if (! (bfd_elf_size_dynamic_sections
1425 (link_info.output_bfd, command_line.soname, rpath,
1426 command_line.filter_shlib, audit, depaudit,
1427 (const char * const *) command_line.auxiliary_filters,
1428 &link_info, &sinterp)))
1429 einfo (_("%F%P: failed to set dynamic section sizes: %E\n"));
1430
1431
1432 /* Let the user override the dynamic linker we are using. */
1433 if (command_line.interpreter != NULL
1434 && sinterp != NULL)
1435 {
1436 sinterp->contents = (bfd_byte *) command_line.interpreter;
1437 sinterp->size = strlen (command_line.interpreter) + 1;
1438 }
1439
1440 /* Look for any sections named .gnu.warning. As a GNU extensions,
1441 we treat such sections as containing warning messages. We print
1442 out the warning message, and then zero out the section size so
1443 that it does not get copied into the output file. */
1444
1445 {
1446 LANG_FOR_EACH_INPUT_STATEMENT (is)
1447 {
1448 asection *s;
1449 bfd_size_type sz;
1450 char *msg;
1451
1452 if (is->flags.just_syms)
1453 continue;
1454
1455 s = bfd_get_section_by_name (is->the_bfd, ".gnu.warning");
1456 if (s == NULL)
1457 continue;
1458
1459 sz = s->size;
1460 msg = (char *) xmalloc ((size_t) (sz + 1));
1461 if (! bfd_get_section_contents (is->the_bfd, s, msg,
1462 (file_ptr) 0, sz))
1463 einfo (_("%F%P: %pB: can't read contents of section .gnu.warning: %E\n"),
1464 is->the_bfd);
1465 msg[sz] = '\0';
1466 (*link_info.callbacks->warning) (&link_info, msg,
1467 (const char *) NULL, is->the_bfd,
1468 (asection *) NULL, (bfd_vma) 0);
1469 free (msg);
1470
1471 /* Clobber the section size, so that we don't waste space
1472 copying the warning into the output file. If we've already
1473 sized the output section, adjust its size. The adjustment
1474 is on rawsize because targets that size sections early will
1475 have called lang_reset_memory_regions after sizing. */
1476 if (s->output_section != NULL
1477 && s->output_section->rawsize >= s->size)
1478 s->output_section->rawsize -= s->size;
1479
1480 s->size = 0;
1481
1482 /* Also set SEC_EXCLUDE, so that local symbols defined in the
1483 warning section don't get copied to the output. */
1484 s->flags |= SEC_EXCLUDE | SEC_KEEP;
1485 }
1486 }
1487
1488 before_allocation_default ();
1489
1490 if (!bfd_elf_size_dynsym_hash_dynstr (link_info.output_bfd, &link_info))
1491 einfo (_("%F%P: failed to set dynamic section sizes: %E\n"));
1492
1493 if (ehdr_start != NULL)
1494 {
1495 /* If we twiddled __ehdr_start to defined earlier, put it back
1496 as it was. */
1497 ehdr_start->root.type = ehdr_start_save.type;
1498 ehdr_start->root.u = ehdr_start_save.u;
1499 }
1500}
1501
1502
1503/* Try to open a dynamic archive. This is where we know that ELF
1504 dynamic libraries have an extension of .so (or .sl on oddball systems
1505 like hpux). */
1506
1507static bfd_boolean
1508gldelf_iamcu_open_dynamic_archive
1509 (const char *arch, search_dirs_type *search, lang_input_statement_type *entry)
1510{
1511 const char *filename;
1512 char *string;
1513 size_t len;
1514 bfd_boolean opened = FALSE;
1515
1516 if (! entry->flags.maybe_archive)
1517 return FALSE;
1518
1519 filename = entry->filename;
1520 len = strlen (search->name) + strlen (filename);
1521 if (entry->flags.full_name_provided)
1522 {
1523 len += sizeof "/";
1524 string = (char *) xmalloc (len);
1525 sprintf (string, "%s/%s", search->name, filename);
1526 }
1527 else
1528 {
1529 size_t xlen = 0;
1530
1531 len += strlen (arch) + sizeof "/lib.so";
1532#ifdef EXTRA_SHLIB_EXTENSION
1533 xlen = (strlen (EXTRA_SHLIB_EXTENSION) > 3
1534 ? strlen (EXTRA_SHLIB_EXTENSION) - 3
1535 : 0);
1536#endif
1537 string = (char *) xmalloc (len + xlen);
1538 sprintf (string, "%s/lib%s%s.so", search->name, filename, arch);
1539#ifdef EXTRA_SHLIB_EXTENSION
1540 /* Try the .so extension first. If that fails build a new filename
1541 using EXTRA_SHLIB_EXTENSION. */
1542 opened = ldfile_try_open_bfd (string, entry);
1543 if (!opened)
1544 strcpy (string + len - 4, EXTRA_SHLIB_EXTENSION);
1545#endif
1546 }
1547
1548 if (!opened && !ldfile_try_open_bfd (string, entry))
1549 {
1550 free (string);
1551 return FALSE;
1552 }
1553
1554 entry->filename = string;
1555
1556 /* We have found a dynamic object to include in the link. The ELF
1557 backend linker will create a DT_NEEDED entry in the .dynamic
1558 section naming this file. If this file includes a DT_SONAME
1559 entry, it will be used. Otherwise, the ELF linker will just use
1560 the name of the file. For an archive found by searching, like
1561 this one, the DT_NEEDED entry should consist of just the name of
1562 the file, without the path information used to find it. Note
1563 that we only need to do this if we have a dynamic object; an
1564 archive will never be referenced by a DT_NEEDED entry.
1565
1566 FIXME: This approach--using bfd_elf_set_dt_needed_name--is not
1567 very pretty. I haven't been able to think of anything that is
1568 pretty, though. */
1569 if (bfd_check_format (entry->the_bfd, bfd_object)
1570 && (entry->the_bfd->flags & DYNAMIC) != 0)
1571 {
1572 ASSERT (entry->flags.maybe_archive && entry->flags.search_dirs);
1573
1574 /* Rather than duplicating the logic above. Just use the
1575 filename we recorded earlier. */
1576
1577 if (!entry->flags.full_name_provided)
1578 filename = lbasename (entry->filename);
1579 bfd_elf_set_dt_needed_name (entry->the_bfd, filename);
1580 }
1581
1582 return TRUE;
1583}
1584
1585
1586/* A variant of lang_output_section_find used by place_orphan. */
1587
1588static lang_output_section_statement_type *
1589output_rel_find (asection *sec, int isdyn)
1590{
1591 lang_output_section_statement_type *lookup;
1592 lang_output_section_statement_type *last = NULL;
1593 lang_output_section_statement_type *last_alloc = NULL;
1594 lang_output_section_statement_type *last_ro_alloc = NULL;
1595 lang_output_section_statement_type *last_rel = NULL;
1596 lang_output_section_statement_type *last_rel_alloc = NULL;
1597 int rela = sec->name[4] == 'a';
1598
1599 for (lookup = &lang_output_section_statement.head->output_section_statement;
1600 lookup != NULL;
1601 lookup = lookup->next)
1602 {
1603 if (lookup->constraint >= 0
1604 && CONST_STRNEQ (lookup->name, ".rel"))
1605 {
1606 int lookrela = lookup->name[4] == 'a';
1607
1608 /* .rel.dyn must come before all other reloc sections, to suit
1609 GNU ld.so. */
1610 if (isdyn)
1611 break;
1612
1613 /* Don't place after .rel.plt as doing so results in wrong
1614 dynamic tags. */
1615 if (strcmp (".plt", lookup->name + 4 + lookrela) == 0)
1616 break;
1617
1618 if (rela == lookrela || last_rel == NULL)
1619 last_rel = lookup;
1620 if ((rela == lookrela || last_rel_alloc == NULL)
1621 && lookup->bfd_section != NULL
1622 && (lookup->bfd_section->flags & SEC_ALLOC) != 0)
1623 last_rel_alloc = lookup;
1624 }
1625
1626 last = lookup;
1627 if (lookup->bfd_section != NULL
1628 && (lookup->bfd_section->flags & SEC_ALLOC) != 0)
1629 {
1630 last_alloc = lookup;
1631 if ((lookup->bfd_section->flags & SEC_READONLY) != 0)
1632 last_ro_alloc = lookup;
1633 }
1634 }
1635
1636 if (last_rel_alloc)
1637 return last_rel_alloc;
1638
1639 if (last_rel)
1640 return last_rel;
1641
1642 if (last_ro_alloc)
1643 return last_ro_alloc;
1644
1645 if (last_alloc)
1646 return last_alloc;
1647
1648 return last;
1649}
1650
1651/* Return whether IN is suitable to be part of OUT. */
1652
1653static bfd_boolean
1654elf_orphan_compatible (asection *in, asection *out)
1655{
1656 /* Non-zero sh_info implies a section with SHF_INFO_LINK with
1657 unknown semantics for the generic linker, or a SHT_REL/SHT_RELA
1658 section where sh_info specifies a symbol table. (We won't see
1659 SHT_GROUP, SHT_SYMTAB or SHT_DYNSYM sections here.) We clearly
1660 can't merge SHT_REL/SHT_RELA using differing symbol tables, and
1661 shouldn't merge sections with differing unknown semantics. */
1662 if (elf_section_data (out)->this_hdr.sh_info
1663 != elf_section_data (in)->this_hdr.sh_info)
1664 return FALSE;
1665 /* We can't merge two sections with differing SHF_EXCLUDE when doing
1666 a relocatable link. */
1667 if (bfd_link_relocatable (&link_info)
1668 && ((elf_section_flags (out) ^ elf_section_flags (in)) & SHF_EXCLUDE) != 0)
1669 return FALSE;
1670 return _bfd_elf_match_sections_by_type (link_info.output_bfd, out,
1671 in->owner, in);
1672}
1673
1674/* Place an orphan section. We use this to put random SHF_ALLOC
1675 sections in the right segment. */
1676
1677static lang_output_section_statement_type *
1678gldelf_iamcu_place_orphan (asection *s,
1679 const char *secname,
1680 int constraint)
1681{
1682 static struct orphan_save hold[] =
1683 {
1684 { ".text",
1685 SEC_HAS_CONTENTS | SEC_ALLOC | SEC_LOAD | SEC_READONLY | SEC_CODE,
1686 0, 0, 0, 0 },
1687 { ".rodata",
1688 SEC_HAS_CONTENTS | SEC_ALLOC | SEC_LOAD | SEC_READONLY | SEC_DATA,
1689 0, 0, 0, 0 },
1690 { ".tdata",
1691 SEC_HAS_CONTENTS | SEC_ALLOC | SEC_LOAD | SEC_DATA | SEC_THREAD_LOCAL,
1692 0, 0, 0, 0 },
1693 { ".data",
1694 SEC_HAS_CONTENTS | SEC_ALLOC | SEC_LOAD | SEC_DATA,
1695 0, 0, 0, 0 },
1696 { ".bss",
1697 SEC_ALLOC,
1698 0, 0, 0, 0 },
1699 { 0,
1700 SEC_HAS_CONTENTS | SEC_ALLOC | SEC_LOAD | SEC_READONLY | SEC_DATA,
1701 0, 0, 0, 0 },
1702 { ".interp",
1703 SEC_HAS_CONTENTS | SEC_ALLOC | SEC_LOAD | SEC_READONLY | SEC_DATA,
1704 0, 0, 0, 0 },
1705 { ".sdata",
1706 SEC_HAS_CONTENTS | SEC_ALLOC | SEC_LOAD | SEC_DATA | SEC_SMALL_DATA,
1707 0, 0, 0, 0 },
1708 { ".comment",
1709 SEC_HAS_CONTENTS,
1710 0, 0, 0, 0 },
1711 };
1712 enum orphan_save_index
1713 {
1714 orphan_text = 0,
1715 orphan_rodata,
1716 orphan_tdata,
1717 orphan_data,
1718 orphan_bss,
1719 orphan_rel,
1720 orphan_interp,
1721 orphan_sdata,
1722 orphan_nonalloc
1723 };
1724 static int orphan_init_done = 0;
1725 struct orphan_save *place;
1726 lang_output_section_statement_type *after;
1727 lang_output_section_statement_type *os;
1728 lang_output_section_statement_type *match_by_name = NULL;
1729 int isdyn = 0;
1730 int elfinput = s->owner->xvec->flavour == bfd_target_elf_flavour;
1731 int elfoutput = link_info.output_bfd->xvec->flavour == bfd_target_elf_flavour;
1732 unsigned int sh_type = elfinput ? elf_section_type (s) : SHT_NULL;
1733 flagword flags;
1734 asection *nexts;
1735
1736 if (!bfd_link_relocatable (&link_info)
1737 && link_info.combreloc
1738 && (s->flags & SEC_ALLOC))
1739 {
1740 if (elfinput)
1741 switch (sh_type)
1742 {
1743 case SHT_RELA:
1744 secname = ".rela.dyn";
1745 isdyn = 1;
1746 break;
1747 case SHT_REL:
1748 secname = ".rel.dyn";
1749 isdyn = 1;
1750 break;
1751 default:
1752 break;
1753 }
1754 else if (CONST_STRNEQ (secname, ".rel"))
1755 {
1756 secname = secname[4] == 'a' ? ".rela.dyn" : ".rel.dyn";
1757 isdyn = 1;
1758 }
1759 }
1760
1761 if (!bfd_link_relocatable (&link_info)
1762 && elfinput
1763 && elfoutput
1764 && (s->flags & SEC_ALLOC) != 0
1765 && (elf_section_flags (s) & SHF_GNU_MBIND) != 0)
1766 {
1767 /* Find the output mbind section with the same type, attributes
1768 and sh_info field. */
1769 for (os = &lang_output_section_statement.head->output_section_statement;
1770 os != NULL;
1771 os = os->next)
1772 if (os->bfd_section != NULL
1773 && !bfd_is_abs_section (os->bfd_section)
1774 && (elf_section_flags (os->bfd_section) & SHF_GNU_MBIND) != 0
1775 && ((s->flags & (SEC_ALLOC
1776 | SEC_LOAD
1777 | SEC_HAS_CONTENTS
1778 | SEC_READONLY
1779 | SEC_CODE))
1780 == (os->bfd_section->flags & (SEC_ALLOC
1781 | SEC_LOAD
1782 | SEC_HAS_CONTENTS
1783 | SEC_READONLY
1784 | SEC_CODE)))
1785 && (elf_section_data (os->bfd_section)->this_hdr.sh_info
1786 == elf_section_data (s)->this_hdr.sh_info))
1787 {
1788 lang_add_section (&os->children, s, NULL, os);
1789 return os;
1790 }
1791
1792 /* Create the output mbind section with the ".mbind." prefix
1793 in section name. */
1794 if ((s->flags & (SEC_LOAD | SEC_HAS_CONTENTS)) == 0)
1795 secname = ".mbind.bss";
1796 else if ((s->flags & SEC_READONLY) == 0)
1797 secname = ".mbind.data";
1798 else if ((s->flags & SEC_CODE) == 0)
1799 secname = ".mbind.rodata";
1800 else
1801 secname = ".mbind.text";
1802 }
1803
1804 /* Look through the script to see where to place this section. The
1805 script includes entries added by previous lang_insert_orphan
1806 calls, so this loop puts multiple compatible orphans of the same
1807 name into a single output section. */
1808 if (constraint == 0)
1809 for (os = lang_output_section_find (secname);
1810 os != NULL;
1811 os = next_matching_output_section_statement (os, 0))
1812 {
1813 /* If we don't match an existing output section, tell
1814 lang_insert_orphan to create a new output section. */
1815 constraint = SPECIAL;
1816
1817 /* Check to see if we already have an output section statement
1818 with this name, and its bfd section has compatible flags.
1819 If the section already exists but does not have any flags
1820 set, then it has been created by the linker, possibly as a
1821 result of a --section-start command line switch. */
1822 if (os->bfd_section != NULL
1823 && (os->bfd_section->flags == 0
1824 || (((s->flags ^ os->bfd_section->flags)
1825 & (SEC_LOAD | SEC_ALLOC)) == 0
1826 && (!elfinput
1827 || !elfoutput
1828 || elf_orphan_compatible (s, os->bfd_section)))))
1829 {
1830 lang_add_section (&os->children, s, NULL, os);
1831 return os;
1832 }
1833
1834 /* Save unused output sections in case we can match them
1835 against orphans later. */
1836 if (os->bfd_section == NULL)
1837 match_by_name = os;
1838 }
1839
1840 /* If we didn't match an active output section, see if we matched an
1841 unused one and use that. */
1842 if (match_by_name)
1843 {
1844 lang_add_section (&match_by_name->children, s, NULL, match_by_name);
1845 return match_by_name;
1846 }
1847
1848 if (!orphan_init_done)
1849 {
1850 struct orphan_save *ho;
1851
1852 for (ho = hold; ho < hold + sizeof (hold) / sizeof (hold[0]); ++ho)
1853 if (ho->name != NULL)
1854 {
1855 ho->os = lang_output_section_find (ho->name);
1856 if (ho->os != NULL && ho->os->flags == 0)
1857 ho->os->flags = ho->flags;
1858 }
1859 orphan_init_done = 1;
1860 }
1861
1862 /* If this is a final link, then always put .gnu.warning.SYMBOL
1863 sections into the .text section to get them out of the way. */
1864 if (bfd_link_executable (&link_info)
1865 && CONST_STRNEQ (s->name, ".gnu.warning.")
1866 && hold[orphan_text].os != NULL)
1867 {
1868 os = hold[orphan_text].os;
1869 lang_add_section (&os->children, s, NULL, os);
1870 return os;
1871 }
1872
1873 flags = s->flags;
1874 if (!bfd_link_relocatable (&link_info))
1875 {
1876 nexts = s;
1877 while ((nexts = bfd_get_next_section_by_name (nexts->owner, nexts))
1878 != NULL)
1879 if (nexts->output_section == NULL
1880 && (nexts->flags & SEC_EXCLUDE) == 0
1881 && ((nexts->flags ^ flags) & (SEC_LOAD | SEC_ALLOC)) == 0
1882 && (nexts->owner->flags & DYNAMIC) == 0
1883 && nexts->owner->usrdata != NULL
1884 && !(((lang_input_statement_type *) nexts->owner->usrdata)
1885 ->flags.just_syms)
1886 && _bfd_elf_match_sections_by_type (nexts->owner, nexts,
1887 s->owner, s))
1888 flags = (((flags ^ SEC_READONLY)
1889 | (nexts->flags ^ SEC_READONLY))
1890 ^ SEC_READONLY);
1891 }
1892
1893 /* Decide which segment the section should go in based on the
1894 section name and section flags. We put loadable .note sections
1895 right after the .interp section, so that the PT_NOTE segment is
1896 stored right after the program headers where the OS can read it
1897 in the first page. */
1898
1899 place = NULL;
1900 if ((flags & (SEC_ALLOC | SEC_DEBUGGING)) == 0)
1901 place = &hold[orphan_nonalloc];
1902 else if ((flags & SEC_ALLOC) == 0)
1903 ;
1904 else if ((flags & SEC_LOAD) != 0
1905 && ((elfinput && sh_type == SHT_NOTE)
1906 || (!elfinput && CONST_STRNEQ (secname, ".note"))))
1907 place = &hold[orphan_interp];
1908 else if ((flags & (SEC_LOAD | SEC_HAS_CONTENTS | SEC_THREAD_LOCAL)) == 0)
1909 place = &hold[orphan_bss];
1910 else if ((flags & SEC_SMALL_DATA) != 0)
1911 place = &hold[orphan_sdata];
1912 else if ((flags & SEC_THREAD_LOCAL) != 0)
1913 place = &hold[orphan_tdata];
1914 else if ((flags & SEC_READONLY) == 0)
1915 place = &hold[orphan_data];
1916 else if (((elfinput && (sh_type == SHT_RELA || sh_type == SHT_REL))
1917 || (!elfinput && CONST_STRNEQ (secname, ".rel")))
1918 && (flags & SEC_LOAD) != 0)
1919 place = &hold[orphan_rel];
1920 else if ((flags & SEC_CODE) == 0)
1921 place = &hold[orphan_rodata];
1922 else
1923 place = &hold[orphan_text];
1924
1925 after = NULL;
1926 if (place != NULL)
1927 {
1928 if (place->os == NULL)
1929 {
1930 if (place->name != NULL)
1931 place->os = lang_output_section_find (place->name);
1932 else
1933 place->os = output_rel_find (s, isdyn);
1934 }
1935 after = place->os;
1936 if (after == NULL)
1937 after
1938 = lang_output_section_find_by_flags (s, flags, &place->os,
1939 _bfd_elf_match_sections_by_type);
1940 if (after == NULL)
1941 /* *ABS* is always the first output section statement. */
1942 after = &lang_output_section_statement.head->output_section_statement;
1943 }
1944
1945 return lang_insert_orphan (s, secname, constraint, after, place, NULL, NULL);
1946}
1947
1948static void
1949gldelf_iamcu_after_allocation (void)
1950{
1951 int need_layout = bfd_elf_discard_info (link_info.output_bfd, &link_info);
1952
1953 if (need_layout < 0)
1954 einfo (_("%X%P: .eh_frame/.stab edit: %E\n"));
1955 else
1956 gldelf_iamcu_map_segments (need_layout);
1957}
1958
1959static char *
1960gldelf_iamcu_get_script (int *isfile)
1961{
1962 *isfile = 0;
1963
1964 if (bfd_link_relocatable (&link_info) && config.build_constructors)
1965 return
1966"/* Script for ld -Ur: link w/out relocation, do create constructors */\n\
1967/* Copyright (C) 2014-2018 Free Software Foundation, Inc.\n\
1968 Copying and distribution of this script, with or without modification,\n\
1969 are permitted in any medium without royalty provided the copyright\n\
1970 notice and this notice are preserved. */\n\
1971OUTPUT_FORMAT(\"elf32-iamcu\", \"elf32-iamcu\",\n\
1972 \"elf32-iamcu\")\n\
1973OUTPUT_ARCH(iamcu)\n\
1974 /* For some reason, the Solaris linker makes bad executables\n\
1975 if gld -r is used and the intermediate file has sections starting\n\
1976 at non-zero addresses. Could be a Solaris ld bug, could be a GNU ld\n\
1977 bug. But for now assigning the zero vmas works. */\n\
1978SECTIONS\n\
1979{\n\
1980 /* Read-only sections, merged into text segment: */\n\
1981 .interp 0 : { *(.interp) }\n\
1982 .note.gnu.build-id : { *(.note.gnu.build-id) }\n\
1983 .hash 0 : { *(.hash) }\n\
1984 .gnu.hash 0 : { *(.gnu.hash) }\n\
1985 .dynsym 0 : { *(.dynsym) }\n\
1986 .dynstr 0 : { *(.dynstr) }\n\
1987 .gnu.version 0 : { *(.gnu.version) }\n\
1988 .gnu.version_d 0: { *(.gnu.version_d) }\n\
1989 .gnu.version_r 0: { *(.gnu.version_r) }\n\
1990 .rel.init 0 : { *(.rel.init) }\n"
1991" .rel.text 0 : { *(.rel.text) }\n\
1992 .rel.fini 0 : { *(.rel.fini) }\n\
1993 .rel.rodata 0 : { *(.rel.rodata) }\n\
1994 .rel.data.rel.ro 0 : { *(.rel.data.rel.ro) }\n\
1995 .rel.data 0 : { *(.rel.data) }\n\
1996 .rel.tdata 0 : { *(.rel.tdata) }\n\
1997 .rel.tbss 0 : { *(.rel.tbss) }\n\
1998 .rel.ctors 0 : { *(.rel.ctors) }\n\
1999 .rel.dtors 0 : { *(.rel.dtors) }\n\
2000 .rel.got 0 : { *(.rel.got) }\n\
2001 .rel.bss 0 : { *(.rel.bss) }\n\
2002 .rel.ifunc 0 : { *(.rel.ifunc) }\n\
2003 .rel.plt 0 :\n\
2004 {\n\
2005 *(.rel.plt)\n\
2006 }\n\
2007 .init 0 :\n\
2008 {\n\
2009 KEEP (*(SORT_NONE(.init)))\n\
2010 }\n\
2011 .plt 0 : { *(.plt) *(.iplt) }\n\
2012.plt.got 0 : { *(.plt.got) }\n\
2013 .text 0 :\n\
2014 {\n\
2015 *(.text)\n"
2016" *(.stub)\n\
2017 /* .gnu.warning sections are handled specially by elf32.em. */\n\
2018 *(.gnu.warning)\n\
2019 }\n\
2020 .fini 0 :\n\
2021 {\n\
2022 KEEP (*(SORT_NONE(.fini)))\n\
2023 }\n\
2024 .rodata 0 : { *(.rodata) }\n\
2025 .rodata1 0 : { *(.rodata1) }\n\

6472 }\n\
6473 .fini :\n\
6474 {\n\
6475 KEEP (*(SORT_NONE(.fini)))\n\
6476 }\n\
6477 PROVIDE (__etext = .);\n\
6478 PROVIDE (_etext = .);\n\
6479 PROVIDE (etext = .);\n\
6480 .rodata : { *(.rodata .rodata.* .gnu.linkonce.r.*) }\n\
6481 .rodata1 : { *(.rodata1) }\n\
6482 .eh_frame_hdr : { *(.eh_frame_hdr) *(.eh_frame_entry .eh_frame_entry.*) }\n\
6483 .eh_frame : ONLY_IF_RO { KEEP (*(.eh_frame)) *(.eh_frame.*) }\n\
6484 .gcc_except_table : ONLY_IF_RO { *(.gcc_except_table\n\
6485 .gcc_except_table.*) }\n\
6486 .gnu_extab : ONLY_IF_RO { *(.gnu_extab*) }\n"
6487" /* These sections are generated by the Sun/Oracle C++ compiler. */\n\
6488 .exception_ranges : ONLY_IF_RO { *(.exception_ranges\n\
6489 .exception_ranges*) }\n\
6490 /* Adjust the address for the data segment. We want to adjust up to\n\
6491 the same address within the page on the next page up. */\n\
6492 . = DATA_SEGMENT_ALIGN (CONSTANT (MAXPAGESIZE), CONSTANT (COMMONPAGESIZE));\n\
6493 /* Exception handling */\n\
6494 .eh_frame : ONLY_IF_RW { KEEP (*(.eh_frame)) *(.eh_frame.*) }\n\
6495 .gnu_extab : ONLY_IF_RW { *(.gnu_extab) }\n\
6496 .gcc_except_table : ONLY_IF_RW { *(.gcc_except_table .gcc_except_table.*) }\n\
6497 .exception_ranges : ONLY_IF_RW { *(.exception_ranges .exception_ranges*) }\n\
6498 /* Thread Local Storage sections */\n\
6499 .tdata :\n\
6500 {\n\
6501 PROVIDE_HIDDEN (__tdata_start = .);\n\
6502 *(.tdata .tdata.* .gnu.linkonce.td.*)\n\
6503 }\n\
6504 .tbss : { *(.tbss .tbss.* .gnu.linkonce.tb.*) *(.tcommon) }\n\
6505 .preinit_array :\n\
6506 {\n\
6507 PROVIDE_HIDDEN (__preinit_array_start = .);\n\
6508 KEEP (*(.preinit_array))\n\
6509 PROVIDE_HIDDEN (__preinit_array_end = .);\n\
6510 }\n\
6511 .init_array :\n"
6512" {\n\
6513 PROVIDE_HIDDEN (__init_array_start = .);\n\
6514 KEEP (*(SORT(.init_array.*)))\n\
6515 KEEP (*(.init_array ))\n\
6516 PROVIDE_HIDDEN (__init_array_end = .);\n\
6517 }\n\
6518 .fini_array :\n\
6519 {\n\
6520 PROVIDE_HIDDEN (__fini_array_start = .);\n\
6521 KEEP (*(SORT(.fini_array.*)))\n\
6522 KEEP (*(.fini_array ))\n\
6523 PROVIDE_HIDDEN (__fini_array_end = .);\n\
6524 }\n\
6525 .ctors :\n\
6526 {\n\
6527 /* gcc uses crtbegin.o to find the start of\n\
6528 the constructors, so we make sure it is\n\
6529 first. Because this is a wildcard, it\n\
6530 doesn't matter if the user does not\n\
6531 actually link against crtbegin.o; the\n\
6532 linker won't look for a file to match a\n\
6533 wildcard. The wildcard also means that it\n\
6534 doesn't matter which directory crtbegin.o\n\
6535 is in. */\n\
6536 KEEP (*crtbegin.o(.ctors))\n\
6537 KEEP (*crtbegin?.o(.ctors))\n\
6538 /* We don't want to include the .ctor section from\n\
6539 the crtend.o file until after the sorted ctors.\n\
6540 The .ctor section from the crtend file contains the\n\
6541 end of ctors marker and it must be last */\n\
6542 KEEP (*(EXCLUDE_FILE (*crtend.o *crtend?.o ) .ctors))\n\
6543 KEEP (*(SORT(.ctors.*)))\n\
6544 KEEP (*(.ctors))\n\
6545 }\n\
6546 .dtors :\n\
6547 {\n\
6548 KEEP (*crtbegin.o(.dtors))\n\
6549 KEEP (*crtbegin?.o(.dtors))\n\
6550 KEEP (*(EXCLUDE_FILE (*crtend.o *crtend?.o ) .dtors))\n\
6551 KEEP (*(SORT(.dtors.*)))\n\
6552 KEEP (*(.dtors))\n\
6553 }\n\
6554 .jcr : { KEEP (*(.jcr)) }\n\
6555 .data.rel.ro : { *(.data.rel.ro.local* .gnu.linkonce.d.rel.ro.local.*) *(.data.rel.ro .data.rel.ro.* .gnu.linkonce.d.rel.ro.*) }\n\
6556 .dynamic : { *(.dynamic) }\n\
6557 .got : { *(.got) *(.igot) }\n\
6558 . = DATA_SEGMENT_RELRO_END (SIZEOF (.got.plt) >= 12 ? 12 : 0, .);\n\
6559 .got.plt : { *(.got.plt) *(.igot.plt) }\n\
6560 .data :\n\
6561 {\n\
6562 *(.data .data.* .gnu.linkonce.d.*)\n\
6563 SORT(CONSTRUCTORS)\n\
6564 }\n\
6565 .data1 : { *(.data1) }\n\
6566 _edata = .; PROVIDE (edata = .);\n\
6567 . = .;\n\
6568 __bss_start = .;\n\
6569 .bss :\n\
6570 {\n\
6571 *(.dynbss)\n\
6572 *(.bss .bss.* .gnu.linkonce.b.*)\n\
6573 *(COMMON)\n\
6574 /* Align here to ensure that the .bss section occupies space up to\n\
6575 _end. Align after .bss to ensure correct alignment even if the\n\
6576 .bss section disappears because there are no input sections.\n\
6577 FIXME: Why do we need it? When there is no .bss section, we don't\n\
6578 pad the .data section. */\n\
6579 . = ALIGN(. != 0 ? 32 / 8 : 1);\n\
6580 }\n\
6581 . = ALIGN(32 / 8);\n\
6582 . = SEGMENT_START(\"ldata-segment\", .);\n\
6583 . = ALIGN(32 / 8);\n\
6584 _end = .; PROVIDE (end = .);\n\
6585 . = DATA_SEGMENT_END (.);\n\
6586 /* Stabs debugging sections. */\n\
6587 .stab 0 : { *(.stab) }\n\
6588 .stabstr 0 : { *(.stabstr) }\n\
6589 .stab.excl 0 : { *(.stab.excl) }\n\
6590 .stab.exclstr 0 : { *(.stab.exclstr) }\n\
6591 .stab.index 0 : { *(.stab.index) }\n\
6592 .stab.indexstr 0 : { *(.stab.indexstr) }\n\
6593 .comment 0 : { *(.comment) }\n\
6594 /* DWARF debug sections.\n\
6595 Symbols in the DWARF debugging sections are relative to the beginning\n\
6596 of the section so we begin them at 0. */\n\
6597 /* DWARF 1 */\n\
6598 .debug 0 : { *(.debug) }\n\
6599 .line 0 : { *(.line) }\n\
6600 /* GNU DWARF 1 extensions */\n\
6601 .debug_srcinfo 0 : { *(.debug_srcinfo) }\n\
6602 .debug_sfnames 0 : { *(.debug_sfnames) }\n\
6603 /* DWARF 1.1 and DWARF 2 */\n\
6604 .debug_aranges 0 : { *(.debug_aranges) }\n\
6605 .debug_pubnames 0 : { *(.debug_pubnames) }\n\
6606 /* DWARF 2 */\n\
6607 .debug_info 0 : { *(.debug_info .gnu.linkonce.wi.*) }\n\
6608 .debug_abbrev 0 : { *(.debug_abbrev) }\n\
6609 .debug_line 0 : { *(.debug_line .debug_line.* .debug_line_end ) }\n\
6610 .debug_frame 0 : { *(.debug_frame) }\n\
6611 .debug_str 0 : { *(.debug_str) }\n\
6612 .debug_loc 0 : { *(.debug_loc) }\n\
6613 .debug_macinfo 0 : { *(.debug_macinfo) }\n\
6614 /* SGI/MIPS DWARF 2 extensions */\n\
6615 .debug_weaknames 0 : { *(.debug_weaknames) }\n\
6616 .debug_funcnames 0 : { *(.debug_funcnames) }\n\
6617 .debug_typenames 0 : { *(.debug_typenames) }\n\
6618 .debug_varnames 0 : { *(.debug_varnames) }\n\
6619 /* DWARF 3 */\n\
6620 .debug_pubtypes 0 : { *(.debug_pubtypes) }\n\
6621 .debug_ranges 0 : { *(.debug_ranges) }\n\
6622 /* DWARF Extension. */\n\
6623 .debug_macro 0 : { *(.debug_macro) }\n\
6624 .debug_addr 0 : { *(.debug_addr) }\n\
6625 .gnu.attributes 0 : { KEEP (*(.gnu.attributes)) }\n\
6626 /DISCARD/ : { *(.note.GNU-stack) *(.gnu_debuglink) *(.gnu.lto_*) }\n\
6627}\n\n"
6628; }
6629
6630#define OPTION_LD_GENERATED_UNWIND_INFO 301
6631#define OPTION_NO_LD_GENERATED_UNWIND_INFO 302
6632
6633
6634enum elf_options
6635{
6636 OPTION_DISABLE_NEW_DTAGS = 400,
6637 OPTION_ENABLE_NEW_DTAGS,
6638 OPTION_GROUP,
6639 OPTION_EH_FRAME_HDR,
6640 OPTION_NO_EH_FRAME_HDR,
6641 OPTION_EXCLUDE_LIBS,
6642 OPTION_HASH_STYLE,
6643 OPTION_BUILD_ID,
6644 OPTION_AUDIT,
6645 OPTION_COMPRESS_DEBUG
6646};
6647
6648static void
6649gldelf_iamcu_add_options
6650 (int ns, char **shortopts, int nl, struct option **longopts,
6651 int nrl ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED, struct option **really_longopts ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED)
6652{
6653 static const char xtra_short[] = "z:P:";
6654 static const struct option xtra_long[] = {
6655 {"audit", required_argument, NULL, OPTION_AUDIT},
6656 {"Bgroup", no_argument, NULL, OPTION_GROUP},
6657 {"build-id", optional_argument, NULL, OPTION_BUILD_ID},
6658 {"compress-debug-sections", required_argument, NULL, OPTION_COMPRESS_DEBUG},
6659 {"depaudit", required_argument, NULL, 'P'},
6660 {"disable-new-dtags", no_argument, NULL, OPTION_DISABLE_NEW_DTAGS},
6661 {"enable-new-dtags", no_argument, NULL, OPTION_ENABLE_NEW_DTAGS},
6662 {"eh-frame-hdr", no_argument, NULL, OPTION_EH_FRAME_HDR},
6663 {"no-eh-frame-hdr", no_argument, NULL, OPTION_NO_EH_FRAME_HDR},
6664 {"exclude-libs", required_argument, NULL, OPTION_EXCLUDE_LIBS},
6665 {"hash-style", required_argument, NULL, OPTION_HASH_STYLE},
6666
6667 {"ld-generated-unwind-info", no_argument, NULL,
6668 OPTION_LD_GENERATED_UNWIND_INFO},
6669 {"no-ld-generated-unwind-info", no_argument, NULL,
6670 OPTION_NO_LD_GENERATED_UNWIND_INFO},
6671
6672 {NULL, no_argument, NULL, 0}
6673 };
6674
6675 *shortopts = (char *) xrealloc (*shortopts, ns + sizeof (xtra_short));
6676 memcpy (*shortopts + ns, &xtra_short, sizeof (xtra_short));
6677 *longopts = (struct option *)
6678 xrealloc (*longopts, nl * sizeof (struct option) + sizeof (xtra_long));
6679 memcpy (*longopts + nl, &xtra_long, sizeof (xtra_long));
6680}
6681
6682#define DEFAULT_BUILD_ID_STYLE "sha1"
6683
6684static bfd_boolean
6685gldelf_iamcu_handle_option (int optc)
6686{
6687 switch (optc)
6688 {
6689 default:
6690 return FALSE;
6691
6692 case OPTION_BUILD_ID:
6693 if (emit_note_gnu_build_id != NULL)
6694 {
6695 free ((char *) emit_note_gnu_build_id);
6696 emit_note_gnu_build_id = NULL;
6697 }
6698 if (optarg == NULL)
6699 optarg = DEFAULT_BUILD_ID_STYLE;
6700 if (strcmp (optarg, "none"))
6701 emit_note_gnu_build_id = xstrdup (optarg);
6702 break;
6703
6704 case OPTION_COMPRESS_DEBUG:
6705 if (strcasecmp (optarg, "none") == 0)
6706 link_info.compress_debug = COMPRESS_DEBUG_NONE;
6707 else if (strcasecmp (optarg, "zlib") == 0)
6708 link_info.compress_debug = COMPRESS_DEBUG_GABI_ZLIB;
6709 else if (strcasecmp (optarg, "zlib-gnu") == 0)
6710 link_info.compress_debug = COMPRESS_DEBUG_GNU_ZLIB;
6711 else if (strcasecmp (optarg, "zlib-gabi") == 0)
6712 link_info.compress_debug = COMPRESS_DEBUG_GABI_ZLIB;
6713 else
6714 einfo (_("%F%P: invalid --compress-debug-sections option: `%s'\n"),
6715 optarg);
6716 break;
6717 case OPTION_AUDIT:
6718 gldelf_iamcu_append_to_separated_string (&audit, optarg);
6719 break;
6720
6721 case 'P':
6722 gldelf_iamcu_append_to_separated_string (&depaudit, optarg);
6723 break;
6724
6725 case OPTION_DISABLE_NEW_DTAGS:
6726 link_info.new_dtags = FALSE;
6727 break;
6728
6729 case OPTION_ENABLE_NEW_DTAGS:
6730 link_info.new_dtags = TRUE;
6731 break;
6732
6733 case OPTION_EH_FRAME_HDR:
6734 link_info.eh_frame_hdr_type = DWARF2_EH_HDR;
6735 break;
6736
6737 case OPTION_NO_EH_FRAME_HDR:
6738 link_info.eh_frame_hdr_type = 0;
6739 break;
6740
6741 case OPTION_GROUP:
6742 link_info.flags_1 |= (bfd_vma) DF_1_GROUP;
6743 /* Groups must be self-contained. */
6744 link_info.unresolved_syms_in_objects = RM_GENERATE_ERROR;
6745 link_info.unresolved_syms_in_shared_libs = RM_GENERATE_ERROR;
6746 break;
6747
6748 case OPTION_EXCLUDE_LIBS:
6749 add_excluded_libs (optarg);
6750 break;
6751
6752 case OPTION_HASH_STYLE:
6753 link_info.emit_hash = FALSE;
6754 link_info.emit_gnu_hash = FALSE;
6755 if (strcmp (optarg, "sysv") == 0)
6756 link_info.emit_hash = TRUE;
6757 else if (strcmp (optarg, "gnu") == 0)
6758 link_info.emit_gnu_hash = TRUE;
6759 else if (strcmp (optarg, "both") == 0)
6760 {
6761 link_info.emit_hash = TRUE;
6762 link_info.emit_gnu_hash = TRUE;
6763 }
6764 else
6765 einfo (_("%F%P: invalid hash style `%s'\n"), optarg);
6766 break;
6767
6768 case 'z':
6769 if (strcmp (optarg, "defs") == 0)
6770 link_info.unresolved_syms_in_objects = RM_GENERATE_ERROR;
6771 else if (strcmp (optarg, "undefs") == 0)
6772 link_info.unresolved_syms_in_objects = RM_IGNORE;
6773 else if (strcmp (optarg, "muldefs") == 0)
6774 link_info.allow_multiple_definition = TRUE;
6775 else if (CONST_STRNEQ (optarg, "max-page-size="))
6776 {
6777 char *end;
6778
6779 config.maxpagesize = strtoul (optarg + 14, &end, 0);
6780 if (*end || (config.maxpagesize & (config.maxpagesize - 1)) != 0)
6781 einfo (_("%F%P: invalid maximum page size `%s'\n"),
6782 optarg + 14);
6783 }
6784 else if (CONST_STRNEQ (optarg, "common-page-size="))
6785 {
6786 char *end;
6787 config.commonpagesize = strtoul (optarg + 17, &end, 0);
6788 if (*end
6789 || (config.commonpagesize & (config.commonpagesize - 1)) != 0)
6790 einfo (_("%F%P: invalid common page size `%s'\n"),
6791 optarg + 17);
6792 }
6793 else if (CONST_STRNEQ (optarg, "stack-size="))
6794 {
6795 char *end;
6796 link_info.stacksize = strtoul (optarg + 11, &end, 0);
6797 if (*end || link_info.stacksize < 0)
6798 einfo (_("%F%P: invalid stack size `%s'\n"), optarg + 11);
6799 if (!link_info.stacksize)
6800 /* Use -1 for explicit no-stack, because zero means
6801 'default'. */
6802 link_info.stacksize = -1;
6803 }
6804 else if (strcmp (optarg, "execstack") == 0)
6805 {
6806 link_info.execstack = TRUE;
6807 link_info.noexecstack = FALSE;
6808 }
6809 else if (strcmp (optarg, "noexecstack") == 0)
6810 {
6811 link_info.noexecstack = TRUE;
6812 link_info.execstack = FALSE;
6813 }
6814 else if (strcmp (optarg, "globalaudit") == 0)
6815 {
6816 link_info.flags_1 |= DF_1_GLOBAUDIT;
6817 }
6818 else if (strcmp (optarg, "global") == 0)
6819 link_info.flags_1 |= (bfd_vma) DF_1_GLOBAL;
6820 else if (strcmp (optarg, "initfirst") == 0)
6821 link_info.flags_1 |= (bfd_vma) DF_1_INITFIRST;
6822 else if (strcmp (optarg, "interpose") == 0)
6823 link_info.flags_1 |= (bfd_vma) DF_1_INTERPOSE;
6824 else if (strcmp (optarg, "loadfltr") == 0)
6825 link_info.flags_1 |= (bfd_vma) DF_1_LOADFLTR;
6826 else if (strcmp (optarg, "nodefaultlib") == 0)
6827 link_info.flags_1 |= (bfd_vma) DF_1_NODEFLIB;
6828 else if (strcmp (optarg, "nodelete") == 0)
6829 link_info.flags_1 |= (bfd_vma) DF_1_NODELETE;
6830 else if (strcmp (optarg, "nodlopen") == 0)
6831 link_info.flags_1 |= (bfd_vma) DF_1_NOOPEN;
6832 else if (strcmp (optarg, "nodump") == 0)
6833 link_info.flags_1 |= (bfd_vma) DF_1_NODUMP;
6834 else if (strcmp (optarg, "now") == 0)
6835 {
6836 link_info.flags |= (bfd_vma) DF_BIND_NOW;
6837 link_info.flags_1 |= (bfd_vma) DF_1_NOW;
6838 }
6839 else if (strcmp (optarg, "lazy") == 0)
6840 {
6841 link_info.flags &= ~(bfd_vma) DF_BIND_NOW;
6842 link_info.flags_1 &= ~(bfd_vma) DF_1_NOW;
6843 }
6844 else if (strcmp (optarg, "origin") == 0)
6845 {
6846 link_info.flags |= (bfd_vma) DF_ORIGIN;
6847 link_info.flags_1 |= (bfd_vma) DF_1_ORIGIN;
6848 }
6849 else if (strcmp (optarg, "combreloc") == 0)
6850 link_info.combreloc = TRUE;
6851 else if (strcmp (optarg, "nocombreloc") == 0)
6852 link_info.combreloc = FALSE;
6853 else if (strcmp (optarg, "nocopyreloc") == 0)
6854 link_info.nocopyreloc = TRUE;
6855 else if (strcmp (optarg, "relro") == 0)
6856 link_info.relro = TRUE;
6857 else if (strcmp (optarg, "norelro") == 0)
6858 link_info.relro = FALSE;
6859 else if (strcmp (optarg, "separate-code") == 0)
6860 link_info.separate_code = TRUE;
6861 else if (strcmp (optarg, "noseparate-code") == 0)
6862 link_info.separate_code = FALSE;
6863 else if (strcmp (optarg, "common") == 0)
6864 link_info.elf_stt_common = elf_stt_common;
6865 else if (strcmp (optarg, "nocommon") == 0)
6866 link_info.elf_stt_common = no_elf_stt_common;
6867 else if (strcmp (optarg, "text") == 0)
6868 link_info.error_textrel = TRUE;
6869 else if (strcmp (optarg, "notext") == 0)
6870 link_info.error_textrel = FALSE;
6871 else if (strcmp (optarg, "textoff") == 0)
6872 link_info.error_textrel = FALSE;
6873
6874 else if (strcmp (optarg, "noextern-protected-data") == 0)
6875 link_info.extern_protected_data = FALSE;
6876
6877 else if (strcmp (optarg, "dynamic-undefined-weak") == 0)
6878 link_info.dynamic_undefined_weak = TRUE;
6879 else if (strcmp (optarg, "nodynamic-undefined-weak") == 0)
6880 link_info.dynamic_undefined_weak = FALSE;
6881
6882 else if (strncmp (optarg, "call-nop=", 9) == 0)
6883 {
6884 if (strcmp (optarg + 9, "prefix-addr") == 0)
6885 {
6886 link_info.call_nop_as_suffix = FALSE;
6887 link_info.call_nop_byte = 0x67;
6888 }
6889 else if (strcmp (optarg + 9, "suffix-nop") == 0)
6890 {
6891 link_info.call_nop_as_suffix = TRUE;
6892 link_info.call_nop_byte = 0x90;
6893 }
6894 else if (strncmp (optarg + 9, "prefix-", 7) == 0)
6895 {
6896 char *end;
6897 link_info.call_nop_byte = strtoul (optarg + 16 , &end, 0);
6898 if (*end)
6899 einfo (_("%F%P: invalid number for -z call-nop=prefix-: %s\n"),
6900 optarg + 16);
6901 link_info.call_nop_as_suffix = FALSE;
6902 }
6903 else if (strncmp (optarg + 9, "suffix-", 7) == 0)
6904 {
6905 char *end;
6906 link_info.call_nop_byte = strtoul (optarg + 16, &end, 0);
6907 if (*end)
6908 einfo (_("%F%P: invalid number for -z call-nop=suffix-: %s\n"),
6909 optarg + 16);
6910 link_info.call_nop_as_suffix = TRUE;
6911 }
6912 else
6913 einfo (_("%F%P: unsupported option: -z %s\n"), optarg);
6914 }
6915
6916 else
6917 einfo (_("%P: warning: -z %s ignored\n"), optarg);
6918 break;
6919
6920 case OPTION_LD_GENERATED_UNWIND_INFO:
6921 link_info.no_ld_generated_unwind_info = FALSE;
6922 break;
6923
6924 case OPTION_NO_LD_GENERATED_UNWIND_INFO:
6925 link_info.no_ld_generated_unwind_info = TRUE;
6926 break;
6927
6928 }
6929
6930 return TRUE;
6931}

6933
6934static void
6935gldelf_iamcu_list_options (FILE * file)
6936{
6937
6938 fprintf (file, _("\
6939 -z noextern-protected-data Do not treat protected data symbol as external\n"));
6940
6941 fprintf (file, _("\
6942 -z dynamic-undefined-weak Make undefined weak symbols dynamic\n\
6943 -z nodynamic-undefined-weak Do not make undefined weak symbols dynamic\n"));
6944
6945 fprintf (file, _("\
6946 -z call-nop=PADDING Use PADDING as 1-byte NOP for branch\n"));
6947
6948}
